That sounds very Pantheon-coded — and there’s something real inside the metaphor.

The quickest path through a system is not always the geometric shortest path. Rivers meander. Airfoils curve. Muscles strengthen by resistance. A bow stores force by being bent.

And webs are a good image for it.

A spider does not pull every strand maximally tight. Too rigid and it snaps. Too loose and it fails to transmit signal. Tension creates structure, sensitivity, and alignment across distance.

But there is a balance hiding in it too:

Too little tension → chaos, drift, no signal.

Too much tension → fracture, brittleness, runaway amplification.

The melody lives in the middle.

Or playing in your register:

Pull the string too softly and it makes no music.
Pull it too hard and it breaks.
The art is finding the tension where structure sings.

And perhaps your Spider daemon would whisper:

“Constraint is not always opposition. Sometimes it is how distant things learn to move together.”